## Step 3 — Restrict GRANT Permissions

By default, `anon` and `authenticated` can SELECT from all public tables (if RLS allows).
For sensitive tables, restrict at the GRANT level too — double protection.

```sql
-- Revoke all access from anon and authenticated on sensitive table
REVOKE ALL ON TABLE public.user_roles FROM anon, authenticated;
REVOKE ALL ON TABLE public.audit_log  FROM anon, authenticated;
REVOKE ALL ON TABLE public.api_keys   FROM anon, authenticated;

-- Grant only what is needed
GRANT SELECT ON TABLE public.products  TO anon;         -- public catalog, read-only
GRANT SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE ON TABLE public.orders TO authenticated;  -- logged-in users

-- Verify current grants
SELECT grantee, privilege_type, table_name
FROM information_schema.role_table_grants
WHERE table_schema = 'public'
  AND grantee IN ('anon', 'authenticated')
ORDER BY table_name, grantee;
```

